            >, a web app for snooker referees also a REACT project. <br />but
            for the minute, I made some cool CSS tricks that can keep the space
            occupied. At least for now.
          </p>
          <div class="css-projects">
            <div class="css-project">
              <h3>Here's gallery 1...</h3>
              <p>
                It involves the use of a rotation transformation with a shifted
                center of rotation to make it appear like the images are
                rotating about a certain central point.
              </p>
              <div class="album">
                <img src="images/images(1).jfif" alt="one" />
                <img src="images/images(2).jfif" alt="two" />
                <img src="images/images(3).jfif" alt="three" />
                <img src="images/images(4).jfif" alt="four" />
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="css-project">
              <h3>And 2....</h3>
              <p>
                This mimics the layout of a pie chart only that you hover over a
                slice or click it to reveal the entire image
              </p>
              <div class="pie">
                <img src="images/images(1).jfif" alt="one" />
                <img src="images/images(2).jfif" alt="two" />
                <img src="images/images(3).jfif" alt="three" />
                <img src="images/images(4).jfif" alt="four" />
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="css-project">
              <h3>Then three...</h3>
              <p>
                Still partial reveal but here, hovering or clicking only reveals
                a bigger portion of the image.
              </p>
              <div class="box">
                <img src="images/images(1).jfif" alt="one" />
                <img src="images/images(3).jfif" alt="two" />
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
